title: Kean dominates CNU in second half
text:
Kean dominates CNU in second half Daily Press 
Like four years ago, Christopher Newport endured a rough day in Union, N.J. -- this time in a conference game. 
The Captains (1-4, 1-3 New Jersey Athletic Conference) fell 35-10 at Kean, which didn't yield a point in the second half. Quarterback Charles App ran for three touchdowns for Kean (4-1, 3-1) -- a vastly improved team from the one that won just two games last season. 
The score was almost identical to an NCAA first-round playoff game in 2011, when the Cougars ousted CNU 34-10. 
The Captains went ahead 7-6 on quarterback Arsaiah Robinson's 1-yard touchdown run and Andrew Harper's extra point with 6:47 left in the first quarter. App's 11-yard TD pass to Tyler Hopman gave Kean the lead for good. 
Harper kicked a 29-yard field goal with 7:11 to go in the second quarter, but the Captains never scored again. 
CNU's Tyler Quigley was 21-of-40 for 224 passing yards but was sacked four times. The Cougars shut down CNU's rushing game, yielding just 38 yards on 29 carries. 
Daquan Davis led CNU with 40 yards on 14 rushes. Khiry Weaver (four catches for 73 yards) and Joe Jardine (seven for 67) were CNU's top receivers. 
App was 14-of-22 for 202 yards, with one interception. He ran for 42 yards, but Damian Corredor led the Cougars with 172 yards on 21 rushes. 
Jonathan Schmitt was Kean's top receiver, catching eight passes for 157 yards. 
DIVISION I: 
Penn State 29, Indiana 7: 
Christian Hackenberg threw for 262 yards and two touchdowns, and he ran for two more scores for the host Nittany Lions (5-1, 2-0 Big Ten). 
Hackenberg was 21 of 39. He hit Brandon Polk and DaeSean Hamilton on 39-yard scoring strikes and turned a bootleg into a 1-yard touchdown run for a 19-7 halftime lead. 
Hackenberg scrambled for a 5-yard touchdown in the fourth quarter, and Tyler Davis kicked a 30-yard field goal to cap the scoring. 
Zander Diamont scored on a 12-yard run for the Hoosiers (4-2, 1-2) but completed just 9 of 17 passes for 90 yards before he was injured and replaced by third-stringer Danny Cameron in the third quarter. 
Rhode Island 20, Delaware 0: 
A week after a dramatic home win against William and Mary, the Blue Hens (2-4, 1-2 CAA) fell flat in Kingston, R.I. 
Harold Cooper ran for a career-best 123 yards and a touchdown, and Rhode Island picked up its first victory. 
The Rams (1-5, 1-2 Colonial Athletic Association) posted their first shutout since a 3-0 win over Maine in 2006, 100 games ago. It was URI's first win in the series since 2011. 
The Rams intercepted Joe Walker three times, including Tez Wilson's 25-yard return for a touchdown, URI's first pick-six since 2013. 
Justin Rohrwasser kicked field goals of 28 and 41 yards. 
Delaware outgained Rhode Island 283-239 but missed two field goals. 
DIVISION III: 
Emory and Henry 31, Bridgewater 7: 
Tyree Ward scored three touchdowns, and the defense for the host Wasps (4-1) held the Eagles (3-2) scoreless after the second quarter. 
E&H's Kevin Saxton was 20-of-36 for 271 yards and four touchdowns, including a pair to Ward for the Wasps, who are coached by Hampton native Curt Newsome. 
Washington and Lee 35, Hampden-Sydney 28: 
Connor Chess broke a tie on a 20-yard touchdown run with 2:09 left as the Generals (5-0) won at Hampden-Sydney (3-2). 
W&L, off to its best start in many years, ran for 333 yards on 60 carries. 
The Tigers' Edgar Moore threw for 357 yards and three touchdowns on 28-of-44 passing, but H-SC 
Guilford 55, Shenandoah 38: 
Matt Pawlowski was 18-of-36 for 363 yards and four touchdowns as the Quakers (4-1) won in Greensboro, N.C. 
Adam Smith caught 10 passes for 253 yards and three of those TDs. De'Eric Bell ran for 153 yards and a touchdown on 18 carries. 
Thr Hornets' Hayden Bauserman was 37-of-65 for 450 yards, three touchdowns and an interception. Shenandoah fell to 3-2. 
Catholic 28, Randolph-Macon 20: 
T.J. Tutone passed for 300 yards and two TDs on 28-of-37 accuracy for the Cardinals (3-2) in Washington. Lucas Morley caught 10 of those passes for 112 yards and both TDs. 
Bubby Morgan was 17-of-31 for 275 yards, one touchdown and two interceptions for the Yellow Jackets (1-4). Christian Redman had five catches for 139 yards.
